00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.820
this thing that was offensive.

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:33.820
I'm hoping that person who's
always stepping up on an island

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:36.310
by themselves, I'm hoping they
have partners next time they

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:37.580
step up.

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:39.880
I mean, so it's
no longer, here I

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:42.700
am about to challenge this thing
again because nobody else is

00:09:42.700 --> 00:09:43.758
going to say anything.

00:09:43.758 --> 00:09:45.550
I'm hoping that person
walks in the meeting

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:47.350
and says I'm going
to challenge this.

00:09:47.350 --> 00:09:49.600
And I'm going to have backup,
because somebody else is

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:51.430
going to actually
speak up and say

00:09:51.430 --> 00:09:52.920
I believe what they just said.

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:53.712
So that's the goal.

00:09:53.712 --> 00:09:55.420
NOEILA FENANDEZ ARROYO:
So actually, it's

00:09:55.420 --> 00:09:57.200
very nice to see the room.

00:09:57.200 --> 00:09:58.318
It's very diverse.

00:09:58.318 --> 00:09:59.110
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:09:59.110 --> 00:09:59.590
NOEILA FENANDEZ
ARROYO: And actually,

00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:01.548
something that we're
trying to encourage people

00:10:01.548 --> 00:10:04.230
more and more is, like, we
need allies in other fronts,

00:10:04.230 --> 00:10:05.235
other perspective.

00:10:05.235 --> 00:10:07.360
LUVVIE AJAYI: So I want to
challenge people to even

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:08.510
be beyond allies.

00:10:08.510 --> 00:10:09.760
Allies are passive.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:13.270
So allies are the people who
are, like, yeah, I understand,

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:15.010
and I see that that
thing is not OK.

00:10:15.010 --> 00:10:16.050
That's an ally.

00:10:16.050 --> 00:10:17.560
Cool, that's cute.

00:10:17.560 --> 00:10:20.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:20.230 --> 00:10:24.827
I think we're past the point
where allyship is useful.

00:10:24.827 --> 00:10:26.660
Because a lot of people
will be, like, well,

00:10:26.660 --> 00:10:29.650
I'm an ally because
I do think everyone

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:31.810
should have equal rights.

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:33.283
But then, OK, you think it.

00:10:33.283 --> 00:10:34.700
What are you going
to do about it?

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:36.880
So that's where the
accomplice comes in.

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:38.073
We need more accomplices.

00:10:38.073 --> 00:10:39.490
And those are
people who are going

00:10:39.490 --> 00:10:43.000
to be active about their
beliefs and their thoughts.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.760
So you're the person
who is, like, yes,

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:50.350
I saw that person be
disrespected in the meeting.

00:10:50.350 --> 00:10:52.300
The allies saw it.

00:10:52.300 --> 00:10:54.790
The accomplice walks up
to the person and says,

00:10:54.790 --> 00:10:56.200
are you going to
make any action?

00:10:56.200 --> 00:10:58.180
Do you need my backup?

00:10:58.180 --> 00:10:59.140
That's the accomplice.

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:00.220
We need more accomplices.

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:02.740
Everyone is so comfortable
because you're, like, I'm

00:11:02.740 --> 00:11:03.760
an ally.

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:04.810
And they're, like, yes.

00:11:04.810 --> 00:11:06.220
Yay, me.

00:11:06.220 --> 00:11:09.520
But if you are an ally and
you haven't done anything,

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:12.270
what are you an ally of?

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:15.850
You know, how have you made a
difference in a tangible way.

00:11:15.850 --> 00:11:19.030
So it's a concept that I
learned from the protesters

00:11:19.030 --> 00:11:22.210
of Ferguson, allies
versus accomplices.

00:11:22.210 --> 00:11:24.550
Their whole thing
is we have to be

00:11:24.550 --> 00:11:26.428
more accomplices and less ally.

00:11:26.428 --> 00:11:27.970
NOEILA FENANDEZ
ARROYO: That's great.

00:11:27.970 --> 00:11:29.990
Really appreciate.

00:11:29.990 --> 00:11:33.020
So another metaphor that
you use that I think

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:37.940
helps very much, you talk
about the domino effect,

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:41.450
that people don't have to be
at the front of the rights

00:11:41.450 --> 00:11:42.190
movement.

00:11:42.190 --> 00:11:45.125
But it can be a little act
that can cause that effect.

00:11:45.125 --> 00:11:46.750
Can you can you talk
to us a little bit

00:11:46.750 --> 00:11:48.190
about that perspective?

00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:48.940
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yes.

00:11:48.940 --> 00:11:51.880
It's just the idea
of a domino, when

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:54.880
you hit one and all of
sudden the rest of them fall.

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:56.800
Life kind of operates
the same way.

00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:58.870
There usually has to
be one person that

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:04.150
makes a move, really, one
catalyst who will then allow

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:06.220
everybody else to follow them.

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:09.040
But here's the thing is
we're always afraid to one,

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:10.030
be the catalyst.

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:11.080
Because it is scary.

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:12.730
Because it probably means you're
putting yourself out there.

00:12:12.730 --> 00:12:14.380
It probably means you're
stepping outside your comfort

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:14.905
zone.

00:12:14.905 --> 00:12:18.220
It probably means you're going
to do something scary, right?

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:21.100
And we're always waiting
for that one other person

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:24.190
to do it first, as opposed to
taking it upon ourselves to be

00:12:24.190 --> 00:12:25.400
that person.

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:27.910
So if everybody's waiting
for the one person,

00:12:27.910 --> 00:12:29.642
who's going to be
that one person?

00:12:29.642 --> 00:12:31.600
So I'm always, like,
well, somebody in the room

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:33.430
has to choose and
make the decision,

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:36.730
because it is a decision,
to be the first one, to be

00:12:36.730 --> 00:12:41.800
the domino who will then allow
everybody else to follow them.

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:44.500
For the MeToo movement,
it was to Tarana Burke.

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:47.900
She started the MeToo
organization 12 years ago.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:50.530
So when it became a hashtag
and everyone was, like, MeToo,

00:12:50.530 --> 00:12:51.970
she was, like, oh.

00:12:51.970 --> 00:12:53.500
She was a catalyst.

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:57.238
So if we don't have catalysts,
then how do movements happen?

00:12:57.238 --> 00:12:58.780
Because then we
think about movements

00:12:58.780 --> 00:13:01.750
in terms of these grand
gestures, the Civil Rights

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:04.250
movement, and all
these big things.

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:06.910
So it feels too big for
us as regular people.

00:13:06.910 --> 00:13:10.210
We're just, like, I
can't be that person.

00:13:10.210 --> 00:13:12.400
And I always say,
take the pressure off.

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:14.480
It's not necessarily
about starting a movement.

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:16.510
It's about doing one thing.

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:19.660
And that one thing could
end up spreading wildly,

00:13:19.660 --> 00:13:21.268
but it might not.

00:13:21.268 --> 00:13:22.810
But at least, just
do that one thing.

00:13:22.810 --> 00:13:23.620
Start somewhere.

00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:24.700
So it's, like, a tweet.

00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:26.533
You tweet something,
one person might see it

00:13:26.533 --> 00:13:28.300
or zero people might see it.

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:30.250
Or 30,000 people might see it.

00:13:30.250 --> 00:13:31.510
100,000 people might see it.

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:32.260
You never know.

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:35.380
By just doing the thing
that you're compelled to do

00:13:35.380 --> 00:13:38.080
and not letting the
fear of consequence

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:40.810
always stop you--
because I always

00:13:40.810 --> 00:13:43.425
let people know that
I know in a room

00:13:43.425 --> 00:13:45.050
where I'm sitting in
front of the room,

00:13:45.050 --> 00:13:47.860
I am in a position of
power and privilege,

00:13:47.860 --> 00:13:51.790
even if I sit in a
room as a black girl.

00:13:51.790 --> 00:13:53.830
And in those moments,
my job is to disrupt

00:13:53.830 --> 00:13:55.870
what's happening
because I have the mic.

00:13:55.870 --> 00:13:56.500
Right?

00:13:56.500 --> 00:13:59.290
So we usually
think of ourselves,

00:13:59.290 --> 00:14:03.090
sometimes we think of ourselves
as what we are marginalized in.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:06.090
We think of ourselves
as less powerful

00:14:06.090 --> 00:14:08.280
than we are, just
because we're, like, I'm

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:12.010
a woman in an industry
that is full of men.

00:14:12.010 --> 00:14:14.730
Well, are you the VP
of the department?

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:15.850
You are powerful then.

00:14:15.850 --> 00:14:18.183
You are way more powerful
than certain men in that room.

00:14:18.183 --> 00:14:21.780
Use that power in a way that's
going to push something forward

00:14:21.780 --> 00:14:25.765
and yeah, make the room
that you're in better.

00:14:25.765 --> 00:14:27.390
NOEILA FENANDEZ
ARROYO: That's awesome.

00:14:27.390 --> 00:14:29.640
So you say black girl.

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:30.390
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yes.

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:31.350
NOEILA FENANDEZ ARROYO:
That's actually a theme

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:33.260
that we talk a lot about it.

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:37.080
I was talking with Jacqueline
that runs the black [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:39.180
organization here in Dublin.

00:14:39.180 --> 00:14:41.880
And she tells me that
more and more you see

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:44.360
how these themes interconnect.

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:45.648
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:14:45.648 --> 00:14:48.190
NOEILA FENANDEZ ARROYO: It's,
like, when is the glass ceiling

00:14:48.190 --> 00:14:49.523
and when is the [? iron ?] cast?

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:53.580
How do you choose?

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:57.090
Do you choose something to
battle as a woman, or something

00:14:57.090 --> 00:15:01.093
to battle as a black
person, or actually,

00:15:01.093 --> 00:15:02.510
because we're
seeing more and more

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:03.750
that actually
everything is much more

00:15:03.750 --> 00:15:04.880
complex and interconnected.

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:05.250
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:15:05.250 --> 00:15:07.740
Everything is definitely
more complex, interconnected.

00:15:07.740 --> 00:15:10.830
As a black woman,
I'm seen as black

00:15:10.830 --> 00:15:13.500
first before a
woman often, right?

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:17.520
So when we talk about diversity,
when we talk about power, when

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:20.670
we talk about access,
the black usually

00:15:20.670 --> 00:15:24.250
will come first, because people
see that in a different way

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:25.410
as they see white women.

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:25.910
Right?

00:15:25.910 --> 00:15:29.040
So a white woman is
seen as woman first,

00:15:29.040 --> 00:15:30.660
not white first, woman.

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:33.850
So that means our
issues are different,

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:35.220
and they're multilayered.

00:15:35.220 --> 00:15:39.070
And the things that we hit
against are also different.

00:15:39.070 --> 00:15:42.240
So as a black woman, not only
am I dealing with the womanhood

00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:45.600
and having to make sure I am
not too assertive in a room

00:15:45.600 --> 00:15:51.360
so people don't think I'm
bossy, which I don't care about,

00:15:51.360 --> 00:15:55.230
then I have to deal
with the black.

00:15:55.230 --> 00:15:59.370
Which if you are too
confident, or if you speak up

00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:02.160
without emojis in
your tones, people

00:16:02.160 --> 00:16:05.805
think you're too aggressive,
which I also don't care about.

00:16:05.805 --> 00:16:07.680
But I have the privilege
to not care about it

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:09.350
because I work for myself.

00:16:09.350 --> 00:16:12.960
And I move in spaces
where I don't have bosses.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:15.780
And I understand that people
who are in the offices

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:17.850
are constantly having
to deal with this.

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:21.510
Be clear that the black
woman who is your co-worker

00:16:21.510 --> 00:16:25.470
is constantly checking her email
over and over again before she

00:16:25.470 --> 00:16:27.680
presses send because she's
afraid that somebody's

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:29.880
going to go to HR and
say she's too short

00:16:29.880 --> 00:16:32.820
because she didn't put an
extra please or a compliment

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:33.710
sandwich.

00:16:33.710 --> 00:16:36.130
You know the
compliment sandwich.

00:16:36.130 --> 00:16:38.020
You want to ask
somebody for a report,

00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:39.538
and you need it by 5:00 PM.

00:16:39.538 --> 00:16:41.580
So you have to be, like,
oh, my God, hey, girl, I

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:43.860
love your hair.

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:46.410
You're looking bomb today.

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:47.940
Can I get this report by 5:00?

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:49.440
Your shoes are fire.

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:50.400
Thank you.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:51.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:51.830 --> 00:16:54.383
You've got to send this
email with all these niceties

00:16:54.383 --> 00:16:56.050
and then you put your
ask in the middle,

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:57.592
so people don't
feel-- because if you

00:16:57.592 --> 00:17:00.140
send an email that's, like,
hey, I need this report by 5:00.

00:17:00.140 --> 00:17:01.440
Thanks.

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:02.200
Oh, my God.

00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:03.950
Why is she so sharp
to me in email?

00:17:03.950 --> 00:17:06.480
You're, like, I was on
the go sending this email.

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:07.980
I just sent what I needed.

00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:10.170
You added tone to it--

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:11.339
tone that wasn't there.

00:17:11.339 --> 00:17:14.609
And people have to constantly
do this in corporate.

00:17:14.609 --> 00:17:17.250
And because you have
to do your actual job

00:17:17.250 --> 00:17:21.740
and then massage people's
egos as your second job,

00:17:21.740 --> 00:17:23.369
that is exhausting.

00:17:23.369 --> 00:17:29.060
And oftentimes, when I talk to
people of color in corporate,

00:17:29.060 --> 00:17:32.030
this is a huge
issue, huge issue,

00:17:32.030 --> 00:17:34.370
where they're, like, I
can't show up as myself.

00:17:34.370 --> 00:17:37.040
Because every single
day, I have to play

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:42.080
the role of nonthreatening
black person to my co-worker who

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:45.650
sees me and automatically sees
tone in what I just sent them

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:47.300
when there was no tone.

00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:49.930
So it's one thing
that I always--

00:17:49.930 --> 00:17:52.700
I need people to get out
their feelings in business.

00:17:52.700 --> 00:17:55.590
If your co-worker sends
you a one sentence

00:17:55.590 --> 00:17:58.580
email that's, like, hey, I
need this thing at 5:00 PM.

00:17:58.580 --> 00:18:00.260
Where's the tone?

00:18:00.260 --> 00:18:01.950
Where did you find that tone?

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:03.200
And this happens all the time.

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:04.090
People go to HR.

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:05.882
I know people who work
in HR who are, like,

00:18:05.882 --> 00:18:08.240
yeah, no, the reports I get
are absolutely ridiculous.

00:18:08.240 --> 00:18:09.972
Adults are really sensitive.

00:18:09.972 --> 00:18:11.180
They'll be, like, oh, my God.

00:18:11.180 --> 00:18:12.732
She was just really short to me.

00:18:12.732 --> 00:18:13.940
Why was she short me with me?

00:18:13.940 --> 00:18:15.500
Well, she sends
these emails, right,

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:16.994
where she just asks for stuff?

00:18:16.994 --> 00:18:18.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:21.260
And you're like, what
was she supposed to do?

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:25.270
Write you a tome and a
poem and then [INAUDIBLE]??

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:27.597
So I need adults to
get out their feelings.

00:18:27.597 --> 00:18:29.180
I need people to do
business properly.

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:31.460
And I need people understand
that there's unconscious

00:18:31.460 --> 00:18:33.770
bias that they carry.

00:18:33.770 --> 00:18:35.350
Right?

00:18:35.350 --> 00:18:38.570
The girl who walks in the office
who is not a morning person,

00:18:38.570 --> 00:18:41.090
who's, like, I can't talk
to nobody before 11 o'clock.

00:18:41.090 --> 00:18:42.920
I'm that person.

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:45.040
I can't deal with people
before 11 o'clock.

00:18:45.040 --> 00:18:46.340
So I know I wouldn't
do well in corporate.

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:47.757
You all would just
think I'm rude.

00:18:47.757 --> 00:18:49.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:49.100 --> 00:18:51.600
I would be written up
by HR a couple of times.

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:54.060
So they'd be, like, she
doesn't talk before noon.

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:56.660
Guys, I don't drink
coffee, either.

00:18:56.660 --> 00:18:57.193
So listen.

00:18:57.193 --> 00:18:58.610
I need to get my
energy naturally.

00:18:58.610 --> 00:18:59.900
So give me some hours.

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:02.735
But I need people to understand
that unconscious bias is

00:19:02.735 --> 00:19:06.380
a huge part of our lives.

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:09.530
How we walk in a room and the
things that we automatically

00:19:09.530 --> 00:19:13.220
expect of people and how we
project things on people--

00:19:13.220 --> 00:19:16.320
we're constantly projecting
our own issues on other folks.

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:18.530
So we're, like, well, this
person was mean to me,

00:19:18.530 --> 00:19:20.450
or this person was short to me.

00:19:20.450 --> 00:19:23.570
I had somebody who told
me because I told her

00:19:23.570 --> 00:19:28.020
that the work that she
did, I didn't love it,

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:30.330
I was demeaning her.

00:19:30.330 --> 00:19:33.490
Demean by saying,
hey, like, I actually

00:19:33.490 --> 00:19:36.980
think you should fix that,
because there's this error.

00:19:36.980 --> 00:19:39.250
This person sees
that as demeaning.

00:19:39.250 --> 00:19:40.210
Now think about that.

00:19:40.210 --> 00:19:41.870
It's two things.

00:19:41.870 --> 00:19:43.990
There's always two
stories, right?

00:19:43.990 --> 00:19:46.400
There's always one person
who's, like, well, I'm not sure

00:19:46.400 --> 00:19:47.483
what I did that was wrong.

00:19:47.483 --> 00:19:49.683
There's always one person
who's deeply offended.

00:19:49.683 --> 00:19:51.100
And there's actually
what probably

00:19:51.100 --> 00:19:51.760
happened in the middle.

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:53.480
Yes, maybe I could
have been nicer.

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:56.110
But I doubt the word
demean and attack.

00:19:56.110 --> 00:19:58.030
That's another
thing that happens

00:19:58.030 --> 00:20:02.140
in corporate and in offices
and just in general.

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:06.640
Black women get accused
of bullying co-workers.

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:09.520
People use the word attack
and bully against us

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:14.980
very often, as opposed to being,
like, we had an interaction

00:20:14.980 --> 00:20:16.600
that didn't feel friendly.

00:20:16.600 --> 00:20:18.670
Or it maybe felt short.

00:20:18.670 --> 00:20:21.570
People would actually
be, like, I felt bullied.

00:20:21.570 --> 00:20:23.490
And I'm, like, whoa.

00:20:23.490 --> 00:20:24.990
How did we get there?

00:20:24.990 --> 00:20:26.530
It's subconscious bias.

00:20:26.530 --> 00:20:28.150
And we walk with it every day.

00:20:28.150 --> 00:20:30.097
We carry these chips
on our shoulders.

00:20:30.097 --> 00:20:32.430
And we sometimes think we are
allies to the point we're,

00:20:32.430 --> 00:20:34.630
like, oh, we're so good.

00:20:34.630 --> 00:20:38.630
But a lot of well-meaning people
do racist and prejudiced things

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:42.100
to co-workers, to
friends, friends, right?

00:20:42.100 --> 00:20:44.310
So people they approach
every single day.

00:20:44.310 --> 00:20:46.060
And then when they're
challenged about it,

00:20:46.060 --> 00:20:50.070
they instantly feel
attacked and bullied.

00:20:50.070 --> 00:20:50.570
Right?

00:20:50.570 --> 00:20:54.290
Because when you are not used
to being checked all your life,

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:57.080
any type of challenge will
come across as an attack.

00:20:57.080 --> 00:20:59.330
And it's something that
people deal with all the time.

00:20:59.330 --> 00:21:03.080
And I always wonder if
people are aware that this

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:07.350
happens right under their nose.

00:21:07.350 --> 00:21:11.090
NOEILA FENANDEZ ARROYO: So I
mean what you say is, like,

00:21:11.090 --> 00:21:13.028
it's--

00:21:13.028 --> 00:21:14.570
I wanted to bring
out to be something

00:21:14.570 --> 00:21:17.210
like we are in Google.

00:21:17.210 --> 00:21:19.340
I was sharing with Luvvie,
like, I'm a bit more

00:21:19.340 --> 00:21:20.465
than a year in the company.

00:21:23.510 --> 00:21:26.270
And something that I thought
we were in a better place--

00:21:26.270 --> 00:21:26.600
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:21:26.600 --> 00:21:28.225
NOEILA FENANDEZ
ARROYO: --it's actually

00:21:28.225 --> 00:21:31.152
like how we are creating that
same sense of opportunity

00:21:31.152 --> 00:21:32.610
for every single
one, independently

00:21:32.610 --> 00:21:35.070
of what's your background,
what's your race.

00:21:35.070 --> 00:21:40.370
And actually, even we think we
have created that environment,

00:21:40.370 --> 00:21:41.823
we have a lot of issues.

00:21:41.823 --> 00:21:43.490
And those issues are
not only in the US.

00:21:43.490 --> 00:21:45.370
They are also here
in Dublin, which

00:21:45.370 --> 00:21:48.433
is a pretty significant
multicultural--

00:21:48.433 --> 00:21:49.850
LUVVIE AJAYI: It's
a global thing.

00:21:49.850 --> 00:21:51.050
It's a universal thing.

00:21:51.050 --> 00:21:56.180
I think people always think that
they're better than they are.

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:59.150
We really do.

00:21:59.150 --> 00:22:00.310
And that is real.

00:22:00.310 --> 00:22:04.190
Because you will find that out
when you challenge somebody.

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:07.970
That is really when you find
out if somebody is an ally, when

00:22:07.970 --> 00:22:09.010
you challenge them.

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:11.090
Because you feel like
an ally when you always

00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:12.290
get along with this person.

00:22:12.290 --> 00:22:15.620
But when a moment of conflict,
you instantly switch,

00:22:15.620 --> 00:22:17.180
that person is not an ally.

00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:20.130
When people are challenged,
they show who they really are.

00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:24.080
And I find that, as
a woman, as somebody

00:22:24.080 --> 00:22:26.930
who's challenged men
in certain spaces,

00:22:26.930 --> 00:22:29.120
and the response I've
gotten has been fascinating.

00:22:29.120 --> 00:22:34.760
So I'll tell you the story that
I told shortly in my TED Talk

00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:38.330
about being asked to speak
at a conference in Amsterdam,

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:38.842
Europe--

00:22:38.842 --> 00:22:39.800
I can't remember where.

00:22:39.800 --> 00:22:40.520
I think it was Amsterdam.

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:41.098
Yeah.

00:22:41.098 --> 00:22:42.140
It was a tech conference.

00:22:42.140 --> 00:22:43.820
And they came to me,
sent me an email.

00:22:43.820 --> 00:22:45.682
Said we'd love for
you to come, speak.

00:22:45.682 --> 00:22:46.640
And I was, like, great.

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:48.100
So I sent it to my manager.

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:50.100
My manager passes
it back to them,

00:22:50.100 --> 00:22:51.830
gives them my fee,
talks about what's

00:22:51.830 --> 00:22:54.440
required to have me in a room.

00:22:54.440 --> 00:22:56.720
And they replied back and
said, well, we don't really

00:22:56.720 --> 00:22:57.380
pay speakers.

00:22:57.380 --> 00:23:01.232
So we would give
Luvvie exposure.

00:23:01.232 --> 00:23:02.690
And I was, like,
well, I'm exposed,

00:23:02.690 --> 00:23:03.900
because you came to me.

00:23:03.900 --> 00:23:04.580
So clearly--

00:23:04.580 --> 00:23:05.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:05.080 --> 00:23:07.000
--I'm already very exposed.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:08.030
So I'm good on that.

00:23:08.030 --> 00:23:11.030
Thank you.

00:23:11.030 --> 00:23:13.770
So I was, like,
this is interesting.

00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:16.430
So I went-- I'm part of this
thing called The List, which

00:23:16.430 --> 00:23:22.670
is a list of 250 dope women in
business and media and tech.

00:23:22.670 --> 00:23:23.930
And we talk.

00:23:23.930 --> 00:23:25.370
We tell each other stuff.

00:23:25.370 --> 00:23:28.340
We talk numbers, which is the
stuff that nobody ever does,

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:28.940
right?

00:23:28.940 --> 00:23:30.030
We talk about resources.

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:32.030
So I would go on The List,
and I was, like, hey,

00:23:32.030 --> 00:23:33.697
I was asked to speak
at this conference.

00:23:33.697 --> 00:23:35.420
They say they
don't pay speakers.

00:23:35.420 --> 00:23:36.918
Is that true?

00:23:36.918 --> 00:23:37.960
Is that a blanket policy?

00:23:37.960 --> 00:23:39.793
South by Southwest
doesn't pay any speakers.

00:23:39.793 --> 00:23:41.752
TED doesn't pay any
speakers, across the board,

00:23:41.752 --> 00:23:42.720
no matter who you are--

00:23:42.720 --> 00:23:45.480
so yeah, fair.

00:23:45.480 --> 00:23:47.180
So in 15 minutes.

00:23:47.180 --> 00:23:49.430
I've got about 10 answers
of people being, like, oh, I

00:23:49.430 --> 00:23:50.347
spoke there last year.

00:23:50.347 --> 00:23:52.450
They definitely
paid my way there.

00:23:52.450 --> 00:23:55.760
Oh, I spoke there and
they bought my books.

00:23:55.760 --> 00:23:58.370
Oh, my guy spoke there
and they paid his way

00:23:58.370 --> 00:24:00.770
and bought his books
and paid his travel.

00:24:00.770 --> 00:24:03.235
So I end up collecting
all this information.

00:24:03.235 --> 00:24:04.610
And I realized
that the hierarchy

00:24:04.610 --> 00:24:09.380
was white men were paid to
speak at this conference.

00:24:09.380 --> 00:24:11.330
White women their
travel got paid for,

00:24:11.330 --> 00:24:13.170
so they at least had that.

00:24:13.170 --> 00:24:15.170
And then black women were
asked to pay their way

00:24:15.170 --> 00:24:16.340
to speak there.

00:24:16.340 --> 00:24:19.025
That was a clear pattern.

00:24:19.025 --> 00:24:20.900
So I was, like, oh, I
got to talk about this,

00:24:20.900 --> 00:24:21.983
because this is a problem.

00:24:21.983 --> 00:24:24.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:24.290 --> 00:24:25.250
So I told my agent.

00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:27.208
So I was, like, I'm just
giving you a heads up.

00:24:27.208 --> 00:24:28.820
And I told my
manager, who is here.

00:24:28.820 --> 00:24:29.945
And I was, like, all right.

00:24:29.945 --> 00:24:31.487
I want to talk about
this on a larger

00:24:31.487 --> 00:24:34.025
scale, because I don't think
what's happening here is fair.

00:24:34.025 --> 00:24:35.400
And I'm not going
to talk about--

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:37.900
I'm not even going to say the
name of the conference, right?

00:24:37.900 --> 00:24:39.980
I'm going to give them
the pleasure of that.

00:24:39.980 --> 00:24:42.080
My manager's-- well, my
manager, she knows me.

00:24:42.080 --> 00:24:43.372
She knows I ain't got no chill.

00:24:43.372 --> 00:24:47.180
My agents-- my agents
were, like, oh, my gosh.

00:24:47.180 --> 00:24:48.660
If you do this, this is risky.

00:24:48.660 --> 00:24:51.620
Because what if other
conferences see this and are,

00:24:51.620 --> 00:24:53.913
like, hey, she's a troublemaker.

00:24:53.913 --> 00:24:54.830
We shouldn't hire her.

00:24:54.830 --> 00:24:56.910
I was, like, I am
a troublemaker.

00:24:56.910 --> 00:24:58.060
But you all should hire me.

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:00.530
But I was, like,
I have to do this,

00:25:00.530 --> 00:25:05.007
because in the position of power
that I'm in as a speaker who's

00:25:05.007 --> 00:25:06.590
been at it for over
eight years, who's

00:25:06.590 --> 00:25:09.650
been on some grand stages,
who gets 50 speaking

00:25:09.650 --> 00:25:12.462
engagements every year,
I can put some speaking

00:25:12.462 --> 00:25:13.670
engagements on the line here.

00:25:13.670 --> 00:25:15.410
I can put some
money on the line.

00:25:15.410 --> 00:25:17.950
And because if I can't do that,
who am I expecting to do it?

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:19.970
Is it the person who
just started last week?

00:25:19.970 --> 00:25:22.260
Is it the person who's
never done a major talk?

00:25:22.260 --> 00:25:22.760
No.

00:25:22.760 --> 00:25:24.680
So I'm going to say this.

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:26.360
So I go on Twitter
and I was, like,

00:25:26.360 --> 00:25:27.902
so there's this
conference that makes

00:25:27.902 --> 00:25:30.140
15 million euros a
year that wants me

00:25:30.140 --> 00:25:33.000
to pay my way to speak there.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:34.970
And this is not OK,
because I find out

00:25:34.970 --> 00:25:38.060
this pattern about payment,
this pay inequality.

00:25:38.060 --> 00:25:39.440
Yo, it went crazy.

00:25:39.440 --> 00:25:41.375
People on Twitter were,
like, oh, my gosh.

00:25:41.375 --> 00:25:42.500
That's happened to me, too.

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:44.500
And then people also
figured out the conference,

00:25:44.500 --> 00:25:46.450
because I also did not
not give them clues.

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:49.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:53.900
So people were, like,
oh, is it the Next Web?

00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:54.800
I was, like, yes!

00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:57.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:57.860 --> 00:26:04.860
No chill-- so in The List
is a "Forbes" reporter.

00:26:04.860 --> 00:26:05.610
And she hit me up.

00:26:05.610 --> 00:26:07.390
She was, like, I'm
seeing this thread.

00:26:07.390 --> 00:26:08.250
She said, would
you actually want

00:26:08.250 --> 00:26:09.842
to go on record to
talk about this?

00:26:09.842 --> 00:26:11.550
Because I want to
write a piece about it.

00:26:11.550 --> 00:26:14.220
And I was, like, yeah,
I would go on record.

00:26:14.220 --> 00:26:15.240
She's, like, OK.

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:17.600
And then she hit
up Gary Vaynerchuk,

00:26:17.600 --> 00:26:20.053
because he had keynote
at the conference.

00:26:20.053 --> 00:26:21.970
And Gary decided to go
on record, too, and be,

00:26:21.970 --> 00:26:24.423
like, yeah, no, they paid me.

00:26:24.423 --> 00:26:25.340
Yeah, he backed me up.

00:26:25.340 --> 00:26:28.670
He was, like, no, no, I
definitely got compensated.

00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:31.900
So she wrote this
piece in "Forbes."

00:26:31.900 --> 00:26:32.818
Oh my, gosh.

00:26:32.818 --> 00:26:34.360
And the picture on
the "Forbes" piece

00:26:34.360 --> 00:26:37.090
is my last Google
talk at Menlo Park.

00:26:37.090 --> 00:26:38.857
So it was, like,
Luvvie at Google.

00:26:38.857 --> 00:26:40.190
Hey, they don't want to pay her.

00:26:40.190 --> 00:26:44.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:48.100
So when the piece came
out, the piece goes nuts.

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:51.970
The dude who runs
the Next Web sees it.

00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:54.670
European guy, doubt
he's used to being

00:26:54.670 --> 00:26:58.270
challenged by a black
girl or anybody, really.

00:26:58.270 --> 00:27:01.840
So he sends me and the
"Forbes" write up an email,

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:06.540
where it was three paragraphs of
straight dog whistle language,

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:07.390
right?

00:27:07.390 --> 00:27:10.090
He was, like, well,
you know, yeah, I mean,

00:27:10.090 --> 00:27:11.350
we do pay some speakers.

00:27:11.350 --> 00:27:13.030
We choose to pay,
I mean, the ones

00:27:13.030 --> 00:27:17.380
who we feel have the
value in our market.

00:27:17.380 --> 00:27:19.300
Maybe if Luvvie was--

00:27:19.300 --> 00:27:21.250
maybe if this was a
more urban market,

00:27:21.250 --> 00:27:24.010
Luvvie could command her fee.

00:27:24.010 --> 00:27:27.590
He literally put maybe if
this was a more urban market.

00:27:27.590 --> 00:27:28.850
So let me get this straight.

00:27:28.850 --> 00:27:31.460
You're asking me to come.

00:27:31.460 --> 00:27:34.390
And then you say
because it's not urban,

00:27:34.390 --> 00:27:38.840
because apparently white
people don't understand me,

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:42.770
because you know, I must be
speaking a different language--

00:27:42.770 --> 00:27:47.320
and it was great, because in
that moment he proved my point.

00:27:47.320 --> 00:27:48.890
He actually proved my point.

00:27:48.890 --> 00:27:52.440
It was so good that the
"Forbes" writer copied the email

00:27:52.440 --> 00:27:53.590
and added it to the piece.

00:27:53.590 --> 00:27:54.090
[APPLAUSE]

00:27:54.090 --> 00:27:55.715
NOEILA FENANDEZ
ARROYO: That's awesome.

00:27:55.715 --> 00:27:57.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:57.310 --> 00:27:59.320
LUVVIE AJAYI: And
a couple of people

00:27:59.320 --> 00:28:01.780
actually pulled out from
speaking at it that year.

00:28:01.780 --> 00:28:03.988
I don't know what else is
going on with the Next Web,

00:28:03.988 --> 00:28:06.125
but in those moments,
I think about that guy.

00:28:06.125 --> 00:28:07.000
You know what I mean?

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:13.000
Like, who got challenged in this
way, and bulked up in defense,

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:18.033
as opposed to being,
like, you're right!

00:28:18.033 --> 00:28:20.200
And the fact that he basically
helped prove my point

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:21.182
was sweet.

00:28:21.182 --> 00:28:23.140
Because we don't get
these opportunities often.

00:28:23.140 --> 00:28:24.427
And I was, like, yes.

00:28:24.427 --> 00:28:26.260
And that is the year
that I did my TED Talk,

00:28:26.260 --> 00:28:27.240
three months later.

00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:28.410
NOEILA FENANDEZ
ARROYO: There you go.

00:28:28.410 --> 00:28:29.470
LUVVIE AJAYI: And
I think about--

00:28:29.470 --> 00:28:30.820
and I use that as an
example for people

00:28:30.820 --> 00:28:32.440
whenever they're
afraid of speaking up.

00:28:32.440 --> 00:28:33.720
Because I did put some
money on the line.

00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:34.360
I was afraid.

00:28:34.360 --> 00:28:35.740
I was, like, OK, let me see.

00:28:35.740 --> 00:28:37.790
OK, if I don't get any
more speaking engagements,

00:28:37.790 --> 00:28:40.248
I guess I'm going to have to
write my second book for real.

00:28:40.248 --> 00:28:41.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:44.380
I'm going to have to figure
out a different business model.

00:28:44.380 --> 00:28:46.330
But I knew that it was risky.

00:28:46.330 --> 00:28:49.270
Because, yes, somebody could
see me and be, like, oh, my God.

00:28:49.270 --> 00:28:51.420
If we invite Luvvie to
come, is she going to--

00:28:51.420 --> 00:28:54.490
I don't make a
habit out of talking

00:28:54.490 --> 00:29:00.100
about how people mistreat me in
that way publicly in business.

00:29:00.100 --> 00:29:02.080
I don't.

00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:04.630
And every week, she's,
like, oh, and then

00:29:04.630 --> 00:29:06.970
this person asked me--
because I don't do that.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:09.280
So this was an
extraordinary moment.

00:29:09.280 --> 00:29:12.370
And I'm, like, again,
we have to ask ourselves

00:29:12.370 --> 00:29:14.690
what we are afraid of.

00:29:14.690 --> 00:29:17.360
If the worst thing that
was going to come from that

00:29:17.360 --> 00:29:20.830
was that I would get less
speaking engagements,

00:29:20.830 --> 00:29:23.410
is that worth me
shutting up and letting

00:29:23.410 --> 00:29:27.250
this conference continue to
do pay inequality things?

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:30.557
Is it worth me also
not showing and not

00:29:30.557 --> 00:29:32.140
putting my name on
the line in the way

00:29:32.140 --> 00:29:34.682
that I'm telling other people
to put their names on the line?

00:29:34.682 --> 00:29:36.280
Sometimes the means
justifies the end.

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:38.650
And I just know how it
encouraged other people

00:29:38.650 --> 00:29:40.382
to speak up.

00:29:40.382 --> 00:29:42.340
And oftentimes, the thing
that we're afraid of,

00:29:42.340 --> 00:29:43.973
that consequence doesn't come.

00:29:43.973 --> 00:29:45.640
I didn't get fewer
speaking engagements.

00:29:45.640 --> 00:29:49.690
I actually got more as a result
of speaking up in "Forbes."

00:29:49.690 --> 00:29:51.100
So yeah, do it.

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:51.640
Say it.

00:29:51.640 --> 00:29:53.980
And then let the chips fall.

00:29:53.980 --> 00:29:56.990
Just always ask yourself what
is the worst that could happen?

00:29:56.990 --> 00:29:57.490
OK.

00:29:57.490 --> 00:29:59.440
If it happened, so what?

00:29:59.440 --> 00:30:01.610
Do you die?

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:02.540
No.

00:30:02.540 --> 00:30:03.140
You'll be OK.

00:30:03.140 --> 00:30:04.380
Figure out something else.

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:04.880
OK.

00:30:04.880 --> 00:30:07.640
If you go speak up at HR
because something awful happened

00:30:07.640 --> 00:30:10.850
at work, or you saw something
awful happen to your co-worker

00:30:10.850 --> 00:30:13.290
and you happen to
get demoted for it,

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:16.380
does that mean you
can't get a new job?

